               <p>Born in <placeName>London</placeName>, Chappell was trained as a wheelwright.
                  Drawn into the revival, Benjamin and his brother became lay evangelists in
                     <placeName>London</placeName> and beyond. For example, <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> commented on the benefit of
                  their presence for three months in early <date when="1770">1770</date> in
                     <placeName>Inverness, Scotland</placeName> (<hi rend="italic">Journal</hi>,
                     <date when="1770-04-26">Apr. 26, 1770</date>, <hi rend="italic">Works</hi>,
                  22:226). In the summer of <date when="1774">1774</date> Chappell and his wife
                     <persName>Elizabeth</persName> emigrated to <placeName>North
                     America</placeName>, ending up on <placeName>St John&apos;s (Prince Edward)
                     Island</placeName>. They became lay leaders of the Methodist movement there and
                  Benjamin remained in correspondence with <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>.</p>
            </person>
